EPISODE 4: The Heal/Create Podcast out today!! 

I was lucky enough to interview @india_carney all about her experiences in the music industry and her approach to emotionally sustainable creativity. India is a BOSS and a professional artist that has worked with Dua Lipa, Mariah Carey, Justin Bieber, Lady Gaga, Billie Eilish, Meghan Trainor, H.E.R., and will be joining Christina Aguilera this Summer. 
She’s appeared as a Top 5 contestant on The Voice, been a vocal coach on American Idol, and has basically just done a million incredible things. 

We get behind the scenes of her creative process as well, and hear the practical steps she takes as a performer. 

I LOVE India’s story, and I think you will too! 

Check it out wherever you get your podcasts!

Just singing in someone’s parking lot. 🗣️

This post is not meant to shame anyone. We’ve all been there before. 😂 

It’s a reminder that we’re often way more in control of our voices than we think. Singing takes a LOTTTTTTTTT of effort. It’s not a walk in the park. Singing is probably the least consistent thing you could be doing lol. Your voice rarely shows up the exact same two days in a row. 

So, take care of it. Study it. What does it need?

But don’t walk in to my classroom with all this confusion after you clearly did not do any of the things we talked about. As if I wouldn’t be able to tell. 🙂

I may be yelling. Sorry. 

#funny

I had this epiphany a few weeks ago where, after reflecting on how much I’ve enjoyed having a therapist over the years, I realized I had always been in therapy haha 

Music has been therapy for me. 😌

Literally, the whole point of musical theater is to get you out of comfort zone, teach you other perspectives so you can have empathy and emote, and make you as uncomfortable as you’ll let it. 

I love to sing. The common phrase “music is my escape/release/therapy” has taken on new meaning for me nowadays and I feel SO lucky to be a creative being. 

♥️

Happy mental health awareness month 

📸 @thejordannaheesi

Wé is one of those singers you hope will audition for American Idol and is paired up with you for the season. 

My wish came true. ✨

She walked in and in my head I said, “Oh yeah. We’re gonna work.” 

This entire season, I’ve seen Wé flourish into a version of herself that we’ll only get to see in this moment. I’ve practically committed to memory all the work we’ve done this season, and now she has a different understanding of how to use her vast palette. Going forward, she’s destined to continue to put all her pieces together and blossom into an artist who really knows who she is. Her new single is 🔥 btw 

What I find (about these shows) is that it really is less about winning and more about the relationships you make and the lessons you learn. Having the opportunity to work with a vocal coach whose job it is to be there for you allows you to grow in such a special way if you let it happen. Getting to have genuine connections with singers like @we_ani is one thing that keeps me excited to return as a vocal coach. From my days on The Voice, I will never ever forget the time I spent with my coach, @trelawnyrosevoice ♥️

Wé, I wish all good things for you! Keep being the star that you are! Go follow her and support!

Stick around and read this for a second. And then leave your thoughty thoughts. Mental health awareness month is almost over, and I have a little more to say. ♥️

Over the past couple years, I’ve been noticing that I could benefit from having more compassion for the gray areas in life, which, of course, is actually where most of our time is spent.

Oh such fun. (sarcasm.)

Especially as a Black woman, there’s not a lot of safety in just “f**king around and finding out.” (Sorry if the profanity is offensive, but that’s the most relatable phrase I’ve got for this.) Because often, you’ll “find out” once you get belittled. Or “find out” once you get fired. Or worse. I won’t go there, but… you know. It’s all too easy to get stuck on the outskirts of the gray, focusing on the black and the white of a situation (not race, just right versus wrong).

More and more, I’m understanding why it’s so imperative for everyone, but especially people of color, to put their mental health first. Rarely have we been encouraged to be messy, with safe reinforcements. I’m still learning, and I’ve spent so long resisting the mess for a few reasons. “Messy” can hurt others. “Confusion” can hurt yourself. “Too complex” can make people not want to work with you. “Messy” is gray af. 

But the statement pictured came to mind immediately after a cathartic experience I had, and I wanted to make sure I wrote it down, because it’s true. Differing opinions, conflicting understandings and inconsistencies don’t necessarily mean something is wrong. People are so complex and special. We all come from different environmental backgrounds that set us all up differently and we have to honor that. The fear that we have to address the unknown is real, you just have to take that chance sometimes. Ideally, you can be unafraid to take those chances multiple times.

But, all conflicting things can be true and that can be a-ok. You don’t always have to look for someone or something to blame.

For those of you who don’t know, I sang background for Katy Perry for almost four years. 🤗

Crazy, right?

When I look back on those memories, I feel so grateful and proud. Learning how to blend and sing iconic KP melodies taught me so much about what my voice could do. In singer’s terms, I “pulled up” so consistently that my range had no choice but to expand! I learned ways to be more professional, etiquette that was expected of me as a band member, I strengthened my mix and my chest registers, I explored harmonies and textures, I started to develop this cool but still healthy rasp that I’m not mad at, and met some of my favorite people. I got to travel the WORLD in a way that I never could’ve anticipated. My parents got to see me singing in Amsterdam. We also went to the Red Light District together. Lmao. 

Unfortunately, I wasn’t able to participate in her current Vegas residency BUT I’m glad I was able to make time to support the amazing Katy Perry crew towards the end of their run. The show was INCREDIBLE, and it was an emotional experience that I’m glad I got to have. I hope to have the opportunity to reunite again in music. 

Thank you, @katyperry, for the impact you’ve had on my life and career. Very grateful for you! 💐

♥️

📸 - @thedevinvelez

Honestly I was going to keep this whole thing private but I really got a kick out of this moment with my mom. 🥰

It’s crazy how nothing else matters. 

When you’re in a hospital bed, all that matters is you. Your connection to God/spirit/universe/self. Your relationships. Friends & family. The little and big reminders that you are loved. Your connection to your body as you decide to trust a surgeon to put you under and take care of it. Your awareness of your internal process as the anesthesia wears off and you feel your entire body again. 

The deadlines, the phone, the work. Dare I say they cease to matter. 

I love you all. Go get checked please. And for the love God, if you feel something, say something. 

I’m ok and back home resting, btw. No need to worry. 

But if you’ve been wondering, that’s where I’ve been. 💜

And.. what do we think?! A summer bop maybe?!
 
•

It pains me to follow the news right now. No human deserves this treatment. No one. No one. We seem to forget that we’re all human for some reason. At this time, all I have to offer is my music, along with my support to those near and far, affected by what’s happening. As I check in on my loved ones, you are all in my thoughts.

THANK you to @drjameslentpiano for joining me and playing beautifully on this here piano, @julianagondek for helping me prep, @_juansol for taking footage and @thedevinvelez for additional footage/moral support. Gotta thank everyone.
